          <head type="note" n="3" xml:id="spp-126-14W2-headnote-3">
            <lg n="1" xml:id="spp-126-14W2-headnote-3-line-group-1" type="headnote">
              <l n="1" xml:id="spp-126-14W2-headnote-3-line-group-1-line-1"></l>
            </lg>
          </head>
          <lg n="1">
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-1" n="1">W<hi rend="small-caps">HOEVER</hi> pleases to inquire</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-2" n="2">Why yonder steeple wants a spire,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-3" n="3">The grey old fellow, Poet Joe,<note place="foot">·Mr Beaumont of Trim, remarkable, though not a very old man, for venerable white locks.</note></l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-4" n="4">The philosophic cause will shew.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-5" n="5">Once on a time a western blast,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-6" n="6">At least twelve inches overcast,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-7" n="7">Reckoning roof, weathercock, and all,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-8" n="8">Which came with a prodigious fall;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-9" n="9">And, tumbling topsy-turvy round,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-10" n="10">Lit with its bottom on the ground:</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-11" n="11">For, by the laws of gravitation,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-12" n="12">It fell into its proper station.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-13" n="13">This is the little strutting pile</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-14" n="14">You see just by the churchyard stile;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-15" n="15">The walls in tumbling gave a knock,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-16" n="16">And thus the steeple got a shock;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-17" n="17">From whence the neighbouring farmer calls</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-18" n="18">The steeple, Knock; the vicar, Walls.<note place="foot">·Archdeacon Wall, a correspondent of Swift's.── F.</note></l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-19" n="19">The vicar once a-week creeps in,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-20" n="20">Sits with his knees up to his chin;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-21" n="21">Here cons his notes, and takes a whet,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-22" n="22">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-23" n="23">Till the small ragged flock is met.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-24" n="24">A traveller, who by did pass,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-25" n="25">Observed the roof behind the grass;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-26" n="26">On tiptoe stood, and rear'd his snout,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-27" n="27">And saw the parson creeping out:</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-28" n="28">Was much surprised to see a crow</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-29" n="29">Venture to build his nest so low.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-30" n="30">A schoolboy ran unto't, and thought</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-31" n="31">The crib was down, the blackbird caught.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-32" n="32">A third, who lost his way by night,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-33" n="33">Was forced for safety to alight,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-34" n="34">And, stepping o'er the fabric roof,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-35" n="35">His horse had like to spoil his hoof.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-36" n="36">Warburton <note place="foot">·Dr Swift's curate at Laracor.── F.</note> took it in his noddle,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-37" n="37">This building was design'd a model;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-38" n="38">Or of a pigeon-house or oven,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-39" n="39">To bake one loaf, or keep one dove in.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-40" n="40">Then Mrs Johnson <note place="foot">·Stella.</note> gave her verdict,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-41" n="41">And every one was pleased that heard it;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-42" n="42">All that you make this stir about</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-43" n="43">Is but a still which wants a spout.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-44" n="44">The reverend Dr Raymond <note place="foot">·Minister of Trim.── F.</note> guess'd</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-45" n="45">More probably than all the rest;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-46" n="46">He said, but that it wanted room,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-47" n="47">It might have been a pigmy's tomb.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-48" n="48">The doctor's family came by,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-49" n="49">And little miss began to cry,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-50" n="50">Give me that house in my own hand!</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-51" n="51">Then madam bade the chariot stand,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-52" n="52">Call'd to the clerk, in manner mild,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-53" n="53">Pray, reach that thing here to the child:</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-54" n="54">That thing, I mean, among the kale;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-55" n="55">And here's to buy a pot of ale.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-56" n="56">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-57" n="57">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-58" n="58">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-59" n="59">om.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-60" n="60">The clerk said to her in a heat,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-61" n="61">What! sell my master's country seat,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-62" n="62">Where he comes every week from town!</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-63" n="63">He would not sell it for a crown.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-64" n="64">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-65" n="65">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-66" n="66">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-67" n="67">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-68" n="68">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-69" n="69">om.</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-70" n="70">Poh! fellow, keep not such a pother;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-71" n="71">In half an hour thou'lt make another.</l>
            <l rend="indent(1)" xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-72" n="72">Says Nancy, <note place="foot">·The waiting-woman.── F.</note> I can make for miss</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-73" n="73">A finer house ten times than this;</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-74" n="74">The dean will give me willow sticks,</l>
            <l xml:id="swift-126-14W2-line-75" n="75">And Joe my apron-full of bricks.</l>
          </lg>
